  "prompt": "What is the stage 2 hypertension diet?",
  "response": "The stage 2 hypertension diet is designed to help manage and reduce high blood pressure through healthy eating habits. This diet typically aligns with the Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension (DASH) diet, which has been specifically developed for this purpose. Key components of this diet include:\n\n1. **Fruits and Vegetables**: Aim for 8-10 servings per day. These foods are rich in vitamins, minerals, and fiber, and low in calories.\n\n2. **Whole Grains**: Include whole grains like oats, quinoa, brown rice, and whole wheat products. These provide essential nutrients and fiber.\n\n3. **Lean Proteins**: Opt for lean meats like poultry and fish, as well as plant-based proteins such as beans, lentils, and tofu.\n\n4. **Low-fat Dairy**: Choose low-fat or fat-free dairy products to reduce saturated fat intake.\n\n5. **Nuts and Seeds**: Consume unsalted nuts and seeds in moderation for healthy fats and protein.\n\n6. **Healthy Fats**: Use monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats found in olive oil, avocados, and fatty fish while avoiding trans fats and saturated fats.\n\n7. **Low Sodium**: Limit sodium intake to less than 2,300 milligrams per day, ideally aiming for 1,500 milligrams per day. Avoid processed foods, canned soups, and salted snacks.\n\n8. **Limit Sugar and Refined Carbs**: Reduce intake of sugary beverages, sweets, and refined carbs such as white bread and pastries.\n\n9. **Alcohol**: If you drink alcohol, do so in moderation\u2014up to one drink per day for women and two drinks per day for men.\n\n10. **Fluid Intake**: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to stay hydrated.\n\nIt's also important to incorporate regular physical activity, manage stress, and avoid smoking to support overall cardiovascular health. Always consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian to tailor the diet to your specific needs and medical conditions.",
